Bioconversion  of  chitin-containing  waste  to  N-acetyl-D-glucosamine  (GlcNAc)  is  of  economic  interest.  Highly efficient chitinases are thus desirable.  Bacillus subtilis  is a  well-known  microorganism  for  industrial protein production and biocontrol,  however  its  chitinolytic  enzyme  has  not  been  studied  in  detail.  In  this  study,  BsChi  from  B.  subtilis was recombinantly expressed in Escherichia coli and characterized as a potent  chitinase  for degrading  crystalline chitin substrates  such as α-chitin, β-chitin and crab  shells.  BsChi  was  found  to  outperform  the  well-known  SmChiA  from  Serratia  marcescens  and  the  commercial  chitinase  preparation  from  Streptomyces  griseus  in

degrading crude crab shell which was pretreated by mechanical grinding and protease.  In combination with OfHex1, a β-N-acetyl-D-hexosaminidase from the insect Ostrinia  furnacalis,  BsChi  could  produce  1.63  g  of  GlcNAc  with  95%  purity  from  10  g  of  pretreated  crab shells  with  a yield  of 60%.  Keywords: chitin,  N-acetyl-D-glucosamine,  chitinase  Chitin,  a  β-1,4-linked  linear  polymer  of  N-acetyl-D-glucosamine  (GlcNAc),  is  abundant  in  crab,  shrimp  and  lobster  shells.  Globally,  approximately  six  to  eight  million  tons  of  these  chitinous  wastes  are  produced  annually,  most  of  which  is  dumped  into  the  sea  or  landfill  [1].  However,  GlcNAc  is  a  valuable  material  for  the  chemical  industry  and  has  great  potential  to  be  used  directly  in  food,  medical  and  agricultural  fields  [2-4].  Therefore,  producing  GlcNAc  from  chitinous  wastes  is  of  industrial  interest.  Although  the  traditional  chemical  approach  of  acid  hydrolysis  of  chitin  followed  by  acetylation  is  economic  and  undertaken  on  a  large  scale,  the  process is not environmentally friendly (acidic waste is produced from acid hydrolysis  [2]  and  byproducts  arise  in  the  acetylation  [5]).  Thus,  in  recent  years,  enzymatic  degradation  of  chitin  has  been  of  characteristics  [3,4,6].    chitooligosaccharides  [(GlcNAc)n],  is  the  key  enzyme  in  chitin  degradation  [7,8].

With  the  help  of  other  chitinolytic  enzymes,  such  as  β-N-acetyl-D-hexosaminidase  (Hex)  [9,10]  and  lytic  polysaccharide  monooxygenase  (LPMO)  [11],  chitinases  produce GlcNAc  from chitin-containing raw  materials. Sashiwa et al. (2002) reported  the  first  production  of  GlcNAc  from  chitin  using  crude  chitinase  preparation  from  Aeromonas  hydrophila  H2330  [12].  From  then  on  a  number  of  chitinases  from  different organisms have been purified or heterogeneously expressed and evaluated by  their  chitinolytic  activities  toward  different  chitin-containing  biomasses  [13-28].  Pretreatment  of  the  raw  materials  by  different  methods  [29-32]  and  the  combination  of chitinolytic enzymes  with different  modes of action  [30,33-38]  have been tried to  improve the hydrolytic efficiency. However, the conversion rates of these enzymes are  still  not satisfactory, which  limits their  large-scale commercial application.  Therefore,  exploring  novel  chitinases  with  higher  productivity  is desirable.  circulans  [41]  and  B.  thuringiensis  [42],  degrade  chitin  to  meet  the  demand  of  nutrition  requisition.  For  example,  the  chitin  degradation  system  of  B.  circulans  WL-12,  a  human  pathogen,  has  been  well  studied  that  includes  three  chitinases  (BcChiA1,  BcChiC1  and  BcChiD1)  [41].  The  chitinases  from  B.  subtilis,  a  well-known  microorganism  for  industrial protein production  [43] and biocontrol  [44],  have also been  investigated.  Three chitinases  with different  molecular weights (20.6,

48 and 31 kDa) were purified  from different strains of  B.  subtilis [13,45]. In another  report, a chitinase  gene  from B. subtilis was cloned and expressed  in Escherichia coli  [46]. However, the enzymatic activities of these chitinases toward insoluble substrates  such  as α-chitin  and β-chitin  have  not  been investigated.  and biochemically characterized.  BsChi was  found to be potent  in  the degradation of  crab shells, and outperformed the well-known SmChiA  from Serratia marcescens and  a  commercial  chitinase  preparation  two-component  system  including  BsChi  and  OfHex1  from  the  insect  Ostrinia  furnacalis [47] was introduced  to produce  GlcNAc  from  crab shells.  2. Results and Discussion  3.1 Production and purification of BsChi  BsChi  is  a  multimodular  protein  of  596  amino  acid  residues  with  a  signal  peptide  (residues 9–26), a catalytic domain  (residues 39–431), a FnIII domain  (residues 457– 529),  and  a  chitin-binding  domain  (residues  547–592)  (Fig.  1A).  The  domain  architecture  of  BsChi  is  similar  to  that  of  BcChiA1,  but  BcChiA1  has  two  FnIII  domains  [49].  In  this  study,  the  mature  form  of  BsChi  (residues  38–596)  was  recombinantly expressed  in E. coli  using  the pET28a expression  vector. Recombinant  BsChi  was  purified  from  chromatography.  The  recombinant  enzyme  was  purified  24.9  folds  with  a  yield  of  4.43  mg  per  liter  of  culture.  The  BsChi  ran  as  a  single  protein  band  on  SDS-PAGE  with  an  apparent  molecular  weight  of  68 kDa (Fig.  1B).    3.2 Enzymatic characterization of BsChi  The optimal pH and temperature of BsChi were determined using both the oligomeric

substrate  MU-β-(GlcNAc)2  and  the  polymeric  substrate  α-chitin.  When  using  MU-β-(GlcNAc)2 as substrate, the enzyme was  most active at pH 5.0 and 40 °C (Fig.  2A).  When  using  α-chitin  as  substrate,  the  enzyme  was  most  active  at  pH  6.0  and  40  °C  (Fig.  2B).  The  pH  and  temperature  optimums  of  BsChi  are  similar  to  other  chitinases from B. subtilis NPU 001 [45] and B. subtilis W-118 [13]. When BsChi was  kept at  various  temperatures  for 1  h  in 20  mM sodium phosphate buffer (pH 6.0),  it  was  significantly  inactivated  above  50  °C  and  completely  inactivated  at  80  °C  (Fig.  of  60  °C  (Fig.  2D).  This  Tm  value  is  similar  to  those  of  BthChi74  from  B.  thuringiensis (63.6 °C) [50] and LinChi35 from Listeria innocua (60.8 °C) [51], but is  higher  than  that  of  LinChi78  from  L. innocua (51.5 °C).    to  test  the  robustness  of  BsChi  toward  potential  environmental  factors  during  industrial application. As shown  in Fig. 3A,  BsChi  could  hydrolyze  both  α-chitin  and  β-chitin  but  had  lower  activity  toward  α-chitin.  This  preference  has  been  known  for  several  other  chitinases,  such  as  LlChi18A from Lactococcus lactis ssp. lactis [52] and SmChiA, SmChiB and SmChiC  from S. marcescens [53]. Moreover, the decrease of  BsChi activity  with  increment of  reaction time toward α-chitin by 22 folds (from 7.5  mM  min-1 at the 1st h to 0.33 mM  min-1 at  the 12th h) was  more obvious than that toward β-chitin by a 3  folds decrease  (from  15.5 mM  min-1  at the 1st h to 5 mM min-1  at the 12th h).

α-chitin  and  β-chitin  by  BsChi  primarily  yielded  (GlcNAc)2  and  a  small  amount  of  GlcNAc.  The  ratio  of  (GlcNAc)2/(GlcNAc)3,  which  was  used  to  evaluate  the  processivity of chitinases [48,53,54], was determined to be 6.1  when the degradation  product of β-chitin by  BsChi  was analyzed. Considering the  values of the processive  SmChiA  (7.3)  and  the  non-processive  SmChiC  (4.1),  BsChi  is  more  likely  to  be  a  processive chitinase  which performs  multiple cleavages to release (GlcNAc)2 without  leaving  the  chitin  chains  .    3.4 Hydrolysis  of crab shell by BsChi  The  kinetic  parameters  of  BsChi  were  determined  using  oligomeric  substrate  The  hydrolysis  products  were  analyzed  by  HPLC  (Fig.  3B). SmChiA  is  a  well-studied  chitinase  with  the  highest  hydrolytic activities toward both α-chitin and β-chitin among chitinases  from  S. marcescens [53]. 3.6 A binary recipe for producing GlcNAc from crab shells  Chitinase  should  work  in  concert  with  Hex  to  produce  GlcNAc  from  chitin.  Insect  OfHex1  has  been  found  to  be  more  potent  than  the  bacterial  analog  SmChb  from  S.  marcescens [47]. In our recent work, 1.5%  OfHex1  in the enzyme cocktail  was  found  to be enough to convert all the  (GlcNAc)n produced by chitinases  into GlcNAc  [36].  Therefore,  a  mixture  of  98.5%  BsChi  and  1.5%  OfHex1  was  made  and  the  dose  response  curves  for  the  “BsChi- OfHex1”  mix  were  determined  using  PFCSP  as  the  substrate.  As  shown  in  Fig.  6,  a  yield  of  1.63  g/L  (8  μM)  GlcNAc  with  95%  purity  was obtained from 10 g/L PFCSP in 24 h. It is noteworthy that 30 μM enzyme loading  was  enough  to  produce  90%  of  the  maximal  GlcNAc  yield,  although  the  maximum  GlcNAc  yield  was obtained at 40 μM. If the chitin  content of the crab shell  was 26.6%  [58], the GlcNAc  yield  was about  60%.    In this study, BsChi from B. subtilis that showed high activity toward crystalline chitin  substrates  was  reported,  and  an  environment-friendly  strategy  by  using  it  for  producing GlcNAc from crab shell wastes was provided. Future work will be focused  on exploring chitinolytic enzymes that synergistically work with BsChi to enhance the  efficiency  of chitin  bioconversion.
